define_metric(25.10)                                      define_metric(25.10)

Name define_metric - Defines new metrics that are required by the user
Syntax
Parameters    -compare   {more_better   less_better   more_better_below_target
       less_better_above_target more_better_ignore_positive}    Specifies  the
       compare  function,  {more_better  less_better  more_better_below_target
       less_better_above_target more_better_ignore_positive}.  The  comparison
       options show the good or bad color when the value is below or above the
       target  value  as  appropriate.  Data_type: enum, optional -description
       <metricDescription> Specifies the description of the metric. Data_type:
       string, optional -id <databaseID> Specifies the database ID. Data_type:
       string, optional -inheritance_tcl <TclName> Specifies Tcl for combining
       children values. The metric is not executed in  the  global  namespace.
       The  equivalent  proc  args  is {children}. Data_type: string, optional
       -name <metric_name > Specifies  the  name  of  the  metric.  Data_type:
       string,  required  -no_inheritance Disables the inheritance of the met-
       ric. Data_type: bool, optional -help Outputs a brief  description  that
       includes type and default information for each define_metric parameter.
       For  a  detailed  description of the command and all of its parameters,
       use the man  command:  man  define_metric  -precision  <number_of_deci-
       mal_places>   Specifies  the  number  of  decimal  places.  Default:  0
       Data_type: int, optional -target <metric_name> Specifies the target  or
       the  name of metric containing the target value. Data_type: string, op-
       tional -tcl { <TCL_command_list> } Specifies the list of  TCL  commands
       or proc to generate (return) the metric which is of the format {<value>
       <unit>}. When the -tcl option is specified, the TCL associated with the
       metric  will  be  executed  whenever create_snapshot is called, and the
       metric will be captured as part of the snapshot. Data_type: string, op-
       tional -threshold <reporting_unit> Specifies the threshold for  compar-
       ing  numbers  in  HTML. If the delta between the two numbers being com-
       pared is less than the threshold then the metric will be  colored  yel-
       low.  If  it  is outside the threshold, then it is colored red or green
       depending on the compare function i.e. whether more is better  or  less
       is  better.  Data_type: string, optional -tools <listOfTools> Specifies
       the list of tools which the tcl code will run. Data_type:  string,  op-
       tional  -type  <metricType>  Specifies  the  type of metric. Data_type:
       string, optional The various metrics types are:
